"LLM-first" is a design philosophy — the same pattern as "API-first" or "mobile-first," but for AI. Instead of building a system the 
traditional way and bolting an LLM on as a feature afterward, you architect the system around the LLM as the primary interface or 
reasoning engine from the start.

What it means in practice:

• Traditional approach:
  Build a dashboard/CLI/pipeline → later add a chatbot on top
  that can answer questions about it.

• LLM-first approach:
  Design the system so the LLM is the primary way people interact
  with it — natural language in, structured actions out — and the
  underlying APIs/data are built to be LLM-consumable from day one
  (clean schemas, good tool definitions, structured logs) rather
  than retrofitted.

In a DevOps context, LLM-first would look like:

• Instead of "here's a Grafana dashboard, and also a chatbot that
  can summarize it," you design your observability data to be
  queryable by an LLM agent from the start — structured,
  well-labeled metrics/logs it can reason over directly.

• Runbooks written as LLM-executable tool definitions (with
  guardrails) rather than static markdown docs a human reads.

• Terraform/Ansible changes proposed and reviewed through an
  LLM-mediated PR flow rather than an LLM being an afterthought
  reviewer bolted onto existing CI.

